On to the story itself. The bit of exposition at the beginning of chapter 1 explaining the setting made me wince. It’s a bit unoriginal, but I’m assuming the main focus of the story is the romance so that can be forgiven. The exposition itself, though, was unnecessary. It takes away some of the mystique and could have been used as a talking point between characters later, thus making its inclusion more natural. You could even go into more detail explaining how the city became the way it is with such a conversation. If exposition can be told naturally through the story, then it should. Beyond that, chapter 1 failed to hook me. In the chapter, were introduced to the world itself through exposition, the protagonist, Andy, and Duke’s gang, some antagonists. It’s not really clear why I, as the reader, should care about Andy. There’s nothing really in chapter 1 that endears me to Andy and makes me want to care about his fate. Sure, he lost his job and is a victim of Duke’s bullying, but he doesn’t seem very broken up over it and thus it makes it hard to relate. The chapter also ends on a rather lackluster note. In 99% of cases, a first chapter that fails to hook readers is a death sentence for the story. My suggestion here is to probably make the chapters a bit longer. If chapters 1 and 2 were put together, then ending shortly after Andy is caught would have built some intrigue for the next chapter.

1/3 probably

The all-steel Kahrs are okay, and spendy, and hard to find used. The polymer framed Kahrs have spotty QC and mediocre fit and finish. When I say fit and finish, I mean things like sharp edges on the sides of the trigger, sharp edges on the mag release, and so on. Mine had feeding problems, ejection problems, and a trigger that would occasionally fail to reset until I put around 250 rounds through it. It's kind of a weird experience. It's striker-fired, but the trigger pull feels like a DA revolver, except for only being around six pounds. It's smooth but the pull is loooooooooooooooooooong, and the reset is all the way forward. Recoil is not horrible for a gun that weighs under 18 ounces with an empty mag, but the sights are SIG-style bar-and-dot, which you either love or hate, and they seem to be made of aluminum. The front sight is staked in place. They have been known to detach themselves at inopportune moments. The trigger took a lot of getting used to. I came to the Kahrs from other platforms where I could ride the reset in rapid fire. With the Kahr that doesn't work so good. I was eventually able to train around it, and I do like how thin it is, and having eight rounds on tap. There are aftermarket mag springs and followers you can put in the factory mags that bring it up from 7+1 to 8+1 but I hear they don't always work very well.
